you have your brewing vessel, you'll need one other KEY IMPORTANT THIS IS THE ONE THING THAT MATTERS MOST TO EVER COFFEE LOVER, you'll need a grinder, be it an electronic one or a hand one. an electric one will make this easier for you, but don't bother spending less than Â£100 on a proper one. hand grinders you can get for cheaper and may not be as good but will still do a good job, make sure your grinder has ceramic burrs. a grinder is important to maintain consistency for each cup, a bad grinder will not grind your coffee beans up evenly, which means you'll end up with under/over extracted cups of coffee. you should care about these things because you're trying to make an effort to do something right, if you're not going to bother then just go back to drinking instant crap.

onto the coffee itself, now i'm not a pretentious asshole, so far these words have not been very specific and thats because it doesn't take much to make great coffee, there is no one thing by any one brand you must have, i've told you what is important and what tools you need, which you decide to use is up to you, whether thats an aeropress or a french press, they all produce different results, different tasting coffee, and everyone has different tastes, so experiment, cause coffee making is a science, and what got me deeply in love with coffee was as i went from instant coffee to fresh coffee, i could taste the change every step of the way, do you smoke, drink or get high on anything at all? thats what good coffee will taste like as you improve your technique, you'll really taste the change and be shocked at how the tinest differences can make the biggest change in the world.

for coffee all that's important is you make the effort to explore your area, as you pass by any cafe or coffee shop, take a peek through the window or pop in and look by their espresso machines for the bags of coffee, usually they'll sell these. don't buy any coffee that doesn't include on the packaging, the date it was roasted, and don't buy from anywhere that has 2 month + old bags sitting on their shelf. coffee doesn't go bad, though it does lose some freshness, you should still be aiming to only buy bags that have been roasted within the past week or two, always ask for the freshest bag they have (though be mindful coffee needs a few days from it's roast date before it is good to drink). now you should have a hand grinder or some grinder, so make sure you are buying whole beans, this is how you get the freshest and bestest tasting coffee, rather than pre-ground stuff thats lost flavour and lovely coffee oils weeks ago. thats all there really is to the coffee, buy locally, buy fresh, buy whole. there's more intricacies such as regions and single origin vs blend (single origin is beans sourced from one farm/source and has more pronounced flavour notes, definitely what i would recommend, wereas blend is usually a mixture of beans, whats important is there are two kinds of beans, arabica and robusta, arabica are the more flavourful beans wereas robusta are usually considered less so and more bitter and so are commonly used for solely for espresso or cheaper coffees, so blends are a mixture of arabica and robusta usually, don't take this to mean it's a lesser coffee, it's all great as long as it's fresh and is your taste. buy from various roasters, take notes on which ones you like most, there are so many great roasters out there that trying out all the different ones could keep you happy forever.

techniques

like the previous words i'll keep this fairly loose, because surprisingly there are hundreds of ways of pouring water on beans to make a cup of coffee, as i mentioned coffee is pretty sciency and so there are loads of recipes and techniques you can find for making coffee with your chosen vessel. i recommend you stick to the default/most common method for your vessel and slowly experiment once you nail the basics. instead i'll tell you what to focus on. your ratio of coffee to water matters and is what most recipes will cover, the typical ratio is either 12:1 or 16:1, water to coffee, it's a good starting point, and then you can adjust to your taste. time is the next important point, but again there are so many ways to do it. typically you'll brew for 1 - 4 minutes. you'll need to stick to a common recipe and develop a taste for under and over extracted coffee, then you can increase or decrease the time or coffee/water amount to get to hit the sweet spot of a perfectly extracted coffee where you can taste all the flavour notes. water is also pretty important, people say mineral water will give you a nicer cup, but it doesn't matter too much, it DOES have an impact on the flavour, but so does the air, it's not worth obsessing this far over it as a solution to better coffee as much as keep it in your mind and try it sometimes, but one thing that is more important concerning water is TEMPERATURE, now like before with ratio and time, these things are all affecting """"extraction"""", there is under cooked food, and burnt food, neither taste very nice, the same is true for real coffee, balance the ratio, time and water temperature, and you'll get a perfectly brewed cup of coffee. again there are various recommendations, the typical temp you want your water to hit is 180-190C, buy a digital thermometer and stick it in your kettle when boiling your water.

this has all assumed that you take your coffee black, this is generally the best way to drink coffee, you will get the most out of the flavours. if you dont take it black it's probably cause you've drank shit coffee your whole life. a good fresh coffee brewed in a certain way can taste very clean and easy to drink, whilst giving you the most delightful caffeine buzz EVER. that being said, i don't drink my coffee black at home, i froth up some milk and cream to add to my coffee, but it's an acquired taste you if you're starting out with fresh coffee you should force yourself to drink it, i was stranded in china for 6 months once and couldn't find any good milk that would froth so drank black for 6 months straight and i don't regret it cause good coffee tastes good. what i will say, is, don't add sugar to your coffee, and if you're going to add milk, buy a milk frother and milk jug, heat a small amount of milk (1/4 the jug or less) in the milk jug on a stove, whilst using your electric frother, you milk will froth up all the way to the top of the jug after a minute or so, remove from heat, you now have thick, foamy, creamy milky goodness, from heating it, it will have a nice nutty sweet flavour to it, and it will sit on top of your coffee rather than mixing completely into your coffee, ruining it by turning it into water coffee flavoured milk. the sweetness from heating it up will also mean you don't need to add sugar. trust me just try it.
